<subSubSection id="EBCDF5AB7737FFF6FF4EFBC50F604F10" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="description">
<paragraph id="A368A6207737FFF6FF4EFBC509EA4EC5" blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FF4EFBC50A184EE9" bold="true" box="[151,297,1148,1174]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Description.</emphasis>
Pale yellow with black pattern on head, pro-, and mesonotum (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA57737FFF6FC2FFBC50FB04EE8" box="[1014,1153,1148,1175]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–47" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1997,2021]" captionTargetBox="[176,1408,535,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-133@11.[174,1412,525,1974]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 29–47. Macropsis spp., lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404167" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404167/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Figs. 36–37</figureCitation>
). Forewings more or less infumose with dark veins. Male darker than female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A368A6207737FFF6FF1EFB7D0A3F4F34" blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
Abdominal apodemes of 2 
<superScript id="54A20B687737FFF6FE2CFB7D09344EAD" attach="left" box="[501,517,1220,1234]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">nd</superScript>
tergite in male wide, rounded, separated by very narrow notch (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA57737FFF6FB30FB7D0EA04EA1" box="[1257,1425,1220,1246]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–203" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[207,1381,183,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[205,1382,181,1843]" captionText="FIGURES 165–203. Macropsis aselae sp. n. (165–182), M. illota (183–189), M. sibirica (190–195), M. megerlei (196), M. emeljanovi (197), M. elaeagni (198–199), and M. scabrosa (200–203). 165–167, 183–184, 190–191, 198, 201―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 168–171, 185–186, 192, 199, 202—the 2nd sternite; 172–174, 187–188, 193–194, 196–197, 200―penis, lateral view; 175–177―pygofer process, lateral view; 178–179―style; 180–182, 189, 195, 203―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457948/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Figs. 190–191</figureCitation>
). Sternal apodemes narrow triangular, separated by U-shaped notch (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA57737FFF6FC53FB5108DC4F7D" box="[906,1005,1256,1282]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–203" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[207,1381,183,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[205,1382,181,1843]" captionText="FIGURES 165–203. Macropsis aselae sp. n. (165–182), M. illota (183–189), M. sibirica (190–195), M. megerlei (196), M. emeljanovi (197), M. elaeagni (198–199), and M. scabrosa (200–203). 165–167, 183–184, 190–191, 198, 201―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 168–171, 185–186, 192, 199, 202—the 2nd sternite; 172–174, 187–188, 193–194, 196–197, 200―penis, lateral view; 175–177―pygofer process, lateral view; 178–179―style; 180–182, 189, 195, 203―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457948/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Fig. 192</figureCitation>
). Penis stem in side view narrow, usually, bent at almost right angle (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA57737FFF6FE23FAB509914F59" box="[506,672,1292,1318]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–203" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[207,1381,183,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[205,1382,181,1843]" captionText="FIGURES 165–203. Macropsis aselae sp. n. (165–182), M. illota (183–189), M. sibirica (190–195), M. megerlei (196), M. emeljanovi (197), M. elaeagni (198–199), and M. scabrosa (200–203). 165–167, 183–184, 190–191, 198, 201―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 168–171, 185–186, 192, 199, 202—the 2nd sternite; 172–174, 187–188, 193–194, 196–197, 200―penis, lateral view; 175–177―pygofer process, lateral view; 178–179―style; 180–182, 189, 195, 203―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457948/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Figs. 193–194</figureCitation>
). 2 
<superScript id="54A20B687737FFF6FD18FAB509E04F65" attach="left" box="[705,721,1292,1306]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">nd</superScript>
valvulae of ovipositor very wide, with one preapical tooth each (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA57737FFF6FF79FA890A334F34" box="[160,258,1328,1355]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–203" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[207,1381,183,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[205,1382,181,1843]" captionText="FIGURES 165–203. Macropsis aselae sp. n. (165–182), M. illota (183–189), M. sibirica (190–195), M. megerlei (196), M. emeljanovi (197), M. elaeagni (198–199), and M. scabrosa (200–203). 165–167, 183–184, 190–191, 198, 201―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 168–171, 185–186, 192, 199, 202—the 2nd sternite; 172–174, 187–188, 193–194, 196–197, 200―penis, lateral view; 175–177―pygofer process, lateral view; 178–179―style; 180–182, 189, 195, 203―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457948/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Fig. 195</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A368A6207737FFF6FF1EFAED0F604F10" blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" box="[199,1105,1364,1391]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
Small species; body length (including tegmina): 
<specimenCount id="B5D16DA97737FFF6FD31FAEC09CE4F10" box="[744,767,1365,1391]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
, 
<quantity id="642F0BC57737FFF6FCD2FAED08A44F10" box="[779,917,1364,1391]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" metricValueMax="3.4" metricValueMin="3.2" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" unit="mm" value="3.3" valueMax="3.4" valueMin="3.2">3.2–3.4 mm</quantity>
; 
<specimenCount id="B5D16DA97737FFF6FC79FAEC08844F10" box="[928,949,1365,1391]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
