<quantity id="642F0BC57737FFF6FC1AFAED0F7C4F10" box="[963,1101,1364,1391]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.65" metricValueMax="3.9" metricValueMin="3.4" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" unit="mm" value="3.65" valueMax="3.9" valueMin="3.4">3.4–3.9 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EBCDF5AB7737FFF6FF1EFAC109BA4FC9" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="A368A6207737FFF6FF1EFAC109BA4FC9" blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FF1EFAC10A374FED" bold="true" box="[199,262,1400,1426]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Host.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA37737FFF6FED7FAC10ACC4FED" box="[270,509,1400,1426]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Spiraea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hypericifolia">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FED7FAC10ACC4FED" box="[270,509,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Spiraea hypericifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in European 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B07737FFF6FD4FFAC109D24FED" box="[662,739,1400,1426]" name="Russia" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Russia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B07737FFF6FD29FAC108474FED" box="[752,886,1400,1426]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, and Central Asia, 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA37737FFF6FB97FAC10FCB4FED" box="[1102,1274,1400,1426]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Spiraea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aquilegifolia">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FB97FAC10FCB4FED" box="[1102,1274,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">S. aquilegifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and, possibly, some other 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA37737FFF6FEC3FA250A404FC9" box="[282,369,1436,1462]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Spiraea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FEC3FA250A404FC9" box="[282,369,1436,1462]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Spiraea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in Transbaikalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EBCDF5AB7737FFF6FF1EFA790A884C5D" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="A368A6207737FFF6FF1EFA790A884C5D" blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FF1EFA790A504FA5" bold="true" box="[199,353,1472,1498]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Distribution.</emphasis>
Steppe zone of Palearctic from European 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B07737FFF6FC80FA7908954FA5" box="[857,932,1472,1498]" name="Russia" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Russia</collectingCountry>
to Eastern Transbaikalia and 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B07737FFF6FADFFA790E464FA5" box="[1286,1399,1472,1498]" name="Mongolia" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
. In Southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B07737FFF6FEF6FA5D0A834F81" box="[303,434,1508,1534]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
is common in steppes in the plains and low mountains; the only 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA37737FFF6FB51FA5C0FCC4F81" authorityName="Lewis" authorityYear="1836" box="[1160,1277,1509,1534]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FB51FA5C0FCC4F81" box="[1160,1277,1509,1534]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Macropsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species abundant outside river valleys.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EBCDF5AB7737FFF6FF1EF9950A4C4DD1" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A368A6207737FFF6FF1EF99508584C14" blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FF1EF9950A014C39" bold="true" box="[199,304,1580,1606]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Remark.</emphasis>
Identification of this species is based on investigation of 
<typeStatus id="7C6C18827737FFF6FC1BF99408C34C38" box="[962,1010,1581,1607]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">type</typeStatus>
specimens from Troitskosavsk (presently Kyakhta Town), Southern Transbaikalia, deposited in ZIN.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A368A6207737FFF6FF4EF9210EB34D61" blockId="12.[151,1437,1688,1966]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
Species feeding on 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA37737FFF6FEA4F9200A844CCD" box="[381,437,1689,1714]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rosa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FEA4F9200A844CCD" box="[381,437,1689,1714]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Rosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA37737FFF6FE2BF92109CC4CCD" authorityName="C.Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[498,765,1688,1714]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Elaeagnaceae" genus="Hippophae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rhamnoides">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FE2BF92109CC4CCD" box="[498,765,1688,1714]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Hippophae rhamnoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are indistinguishable in the shape of the male abdominal apodemes and genitalia and in most cases are also similar in the shape the 2 
<superScript id="54A20B687737FFF6FC02F90508DA4CB5" attach="left" box="[987,1003,1724,1738]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">nd</superScript>
valvulae of the ovipositor. At the same time, they distinctly differ from each other in coloration and can be easily identified by external appearance. For this reason, we give a description of apodemes and genitalia here and omit this section in the descriptions of species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A368A6207737FFF6FF1EF8910A4C4DD1" blockId="12.[151,1437,1688,1966]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
Abdominal apodemes of 2 
<superScript id="54A20B687737FFF6FE2DF89109354D49" attach="left" box="[500,516,1832,1846]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">nd</superScript>
tergite in male wide, rounded, separated by wide round notch, sternal apodemes narrow triangular, separated by U-shaped angular notch. Penis in side view narrow (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA57737FFF6FB9FF8F50FDD4D18" box="[1094,1260,1868,1895]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–203" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[207,1381,183,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[205,1382,181,1843]" captionText="FIGURES 165–203. Macropsis aselae sp. n. (165–182), M. illota (183–189), M. sibirica (190–195), M. megerlei (196), M. emeljanovi (197), M. elaeagni (198–199), and M. scabrosa (200–203). 165–167, 183–184, 190–191, 198, 201―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 168–171, 185–186, 192, 199, 202—the 2nd sternite; 172–174, 187–188, 193–194, 196–197, 200―penis, lateral view; 175–177―pygofer process, lateral view; 178–179―style; 180–182, 189, 195, 203―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457948/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Figs. 196–197</figureCitation>
), bent at almost right angle. 2 
<superScript id="54A20B687737FFF6FEF3F8C90A0B4D01" attach="left" box="[298,314,1904,1918]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">nd</superScript>
valvulae of ovipositor with 4–8 preapical teeth each, only in 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA37737FFF6FC3BF8C80E294DF5" authority="(Horvath, 1904)" baseAuthorityName="Horvath" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[994,1304,1904,1930]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pictipes">
<emphasis id="91A37A327737FFF6FC3BF8C80F6F4DF5" box="[994,1118,1905,1930]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">M. pictipes</emphasis>
(Horvath, 1904)
</taxonomicName>
with 10–13 preapical teeth each.
</paragraph>
